This is the complete brute force solution to the palindrome pairs problem. The intuition is straightforward: we need to check every possible ordered pair of words from the array, concatenate them, and verify if the resulting string reads the same forwards and backwards. This approach works because it exhaustively examines all n² possible combinations, guaranteeing we don't miss any valid pairs. The algorithm starts by initializing an empty result list. We then use nested loops: the outer loop iterates through each word as the first element (i from 0 to n-1), and the inner loop iterates through each word as the second element (j from 0 to n-1). For each pair where i ≠ j (since the problem typically considers distinct indices), we concatenate words[i] and words[j] to form a candidate string. We then check if this candidate is a palindrome by comparing characters from both ends moving toward the center. If it's a palindrome, we add the pair (i,j) to our results. The time complexity is O(n² * k) where n is the number of words and k is the average word length, since for each of the n² pairs we perform O(k) operations to check palindrome status. Space complexity is O(1) excluding output storage. This connects directly to the problem statement as the complete implementation. Common mistakes include forgetting to handle the i ≠ j condition, inefficient string concatenation (which can be optimized by checking palindrome without full concatenation), and not considering empty strings properly. The brute force nature makes it impractical for large inputs but serves as a baseline understanding.

Pseudocode:
function findAllPalindromePairs(words):
    result = []
    n = length(words)
    for i from 0 to n-1:
        for j from 0 to n-1:
            if i != j:
                candidate = words[i] + words[j]
                if isPalindrome(candidate):
                    result.append([i, j])
    return result

function isPalindrome(s):
    left = 0
    right = length(s) - 1
    while left < right:
        if s[left] != s[right]:
            return False
        left += 1
        right -= 1
    return True

